Juan Manuel Alvarez was convicted for causing a fatal train crash in 2005.
Prosecutors argued he staged the incident for attention from his wife.
Alvarez initially planned suicide but changed his mind, leading to the tragedy.
Despite facing murder charges, his troubled past of abuse and mental illness was revealed in court.
The jury recommended life imprisonment, not the death penalty.
Alvarez's defense emphasized his traumatic upbringing, while prosecutors highlighted his manipulative behavior.
The emotional trial shed light on a complex case of personal turmoil and tragic consequences, leaving many questioning the true intentions behind the horrific event.
